## Why This Day Matters

On Day G1 you worked on a single timeline — every commit went straight onto `main`. This is fine for solo warmups. It will **destroy** you on a real project.

Here's why: you're on Day 15 implementing the execution loop. It's half-done — tests are broken, the code doesn't compile. Then you discover a critical bug in
the scope enforcer from Day 19. You need to fix it now. But `main` is broken with your half-finished execution loop. You can't ship a fix without also shipping broken code.

Branches solve this. Your execution loop lives on `phase-4/execution-loop`. `main` is always clean, always compiles, always works. When you need to fix the
scope enforcer, you branch off `main` — which is stable — fix it, merge it back. The execution loop on its own branch is undisturbed.

**Branches are not a complexity feature. They are how you work on something experimental without breaking what already works.**

