## Part 1: What Is a Branch?

A branch in Git is a **lightweight pointer to a commit**. That's it. Not a copy of your code. Not a separate folder. A 41-byte file containing a commit hash.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                         BRANCH MODEL                             │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                                  │
│   Commit history:                                                │
│                                                                  │
│     A ← B ← C ← D ← E                                          │
│                       ↑                                          │
│                      main                                        │
│                       ↑                                          │
│                      HEAD                                        │
│                                                                  │
│   After: git checkout -b feature                                 │
│                                                                  │
│     A ← B ← C ← D ← E                                          │
│                       ↑                                          │
│                      main                                        │
│                      feature ← HEAD                              │
│                                                                  │
│   After committing F and G on feature:                           │
│                                                                  │
│     A ← B ← C ← D ← E ← F ← G                                 │
│                       ↑       ↑                                  │
│                      main    feature ← HEAD                      │
│                                                                  │
│   main didn't move. feature advanced. They diverge.              │
│                                                                  │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Key insight:** When you create a branch, you're not copying files. You're creating a new pointer that starts at the same commit. As you make commits, the
pointer moves forward. `main` stays where it was. The branches have now *diverged* — and that's exactly the point.

**Why this matters for Achilles:** When you build the nmap node (Day 23), you'll work on `phase-7/nmap-node`. Commits pile up on that branch. Meanwhile, `main`
contains your clean, tested code from everything before Day 23. When the nmap node works, you merge it into `main`. If it doesn't work out, you delete the branch.
`main` is never contaminated.

