### Exercise 1 — Push Your Local Repository to GitHub

This is the moment your code becomes public. Your portfolio starts here.

**Step 1: Create a GitHub account** (if you don't have one).

Go to [github.com](https://github.com) and sign up. Use a professional username — this will be on your resume.

**Step 2: Create a new repository on GitHub.**

- Click **"New repository"** (or go to `github.com/new`)
- Repository name: `achilles`
- Description: `Offensive Security Orchestration Engine — CLI-first security automation platform`
- Visibility: **Public** (this is your portfolio)
- **Do NOT** check "Add a README file"
- **Do NOT** check "Add .gitignore"
- **Do NOT** choose a license yet (we'll add Apache 2.0 on Day 36)
- Click **Create repository**

GitHub will show you instructions. Follow the "push an existing repository" section:

**Step 3: Connect your local repo to GitHub.**

```bash
cd achilles-practice
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git
```

Replace `YOURUSERNAME` with your actual GitHub username.

**Understand what just happened:** `git remote add origin <url>` tells your local Git: "there is a remote copy of this repository at this URL,
and I'm calling it `origin`." `origin` is a convention — it means "the primary remote." You can have multiple remotes, but for a solo project, `origin` is the only one you need.

Verify:

```bash
git remote -v
```

Output:

```
origin  https://github.com/YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git (fetch)
origin  https://github.com/YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git (push)
```

**Step 4: Push your history to GitHub.**

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

**Understand the flags:**
- `push` — send commits from your local repository to the remote
- `-u` — set `origin/main` as the "upstream" for your local `main` branch. After this, `git push` alone (no arguments) will push to `origin main` automatically
- `origin main` — push to the remote called `origin`, branch called `main`

**Step 5: Open your browser.** Go to `github.com/YOURUSERNAME/achilles`.

Your commits are there. Your history is visible. Anyone in the world can see it. Click on "Commits" — each one with your clean `type(component):
description` message. This is your portfolio, live.

### Before You Push: Authentication Setup

GitHub no longer accepts passwords for `git push`. You must authenticate using one of the methods below. **SSH is recommended** — set it up once and never think about it again.

---

#### Option A: SSH Key Authentication (Recommended)

SSH keys use public-key cryptography. You generate a key pair: a **private key** (stays on your machine, never shared) and a **public key** (given to GitHub). When you push, Git proves to GitHub that you hold the private key, without ever sending it.

**Step A1: Check if you already have an SSH key.**

```bash
ls -la ~/.ssh/
```

If you see `id_ed25519` and `id_ed25519.pub` (or `id_rsa` / `id_rsa.pub`), you already have a key. Skip to Step A3.

If the directory doesn't exist or is empty, proceed:

**Step A2: Generate a new SSH key.**

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your.email@example.com"
```

- `-t ed25519` — Use the Ed25519 algorithm (modern, fast, secure). Prefer this over RSA.
- `-C "your.email@example.com"` — A comment label, typically your email. This helps identify the key.

When prompted:

```
Enter file in which to save the key (/home/youruser/.ssh/id_ed25519):
```

Press **Enter** to accept the default path.

```
Enter passphrase (empty for no passphrase):
```

**Set a passphrase.** This protects your private key if someone gains access to your machine. You'll use `ssh-agent` so you don't have to type it every time.

**Step A3: Start the ssh-agent and add your key.**

On Arch Linux, `ssh-agent` is included in the `openssh` package (which you almost certainly have). Start it and add your key:

```bash
# Start the agent in the background
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
```

Output: `Agent pid 12345`

```bash
# Add your private key to the agent
ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
```

Enter your passphrase when prompted. The agent now holds your key in memory — you won't be asked for the passphrase again until you log out or reboot.

> **Persistent agent on Arch Linux:** To avoid running `eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"` every time you open a terminal, add it to your shell config:
>
> For **zsh** (`~/.zshrc`) or **bash** (`~/.bashrc`):
> ```bash
> # Start ssh-agent if not already running
> if ! pgrep -u "$USER" ssh-agent > /dev/null; then
>     ssh-agent -t 1h > "$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/ssh-agent.env"
> fi
> if [[ ! -f "$SSH_AUTH_SOCK" ]]; then
>     source "$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/ssh-agent.env" >/dev/null
> fi
> ```
>
> Alternatively, if you use **systemd**, enable the user service:
> ```bash
> systemctl --user enable --now ssh-agent.service
> ```
> Then add `export SSH_AUTH_SOCK="$XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/ssh-agent.socket"` to your shell config.

**Step A4: Copy your public key.**

```bash
cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
```

This prints your public key. It looks like:

```
ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIG... your.email@example.com
```

Copy the **entire line** (including `ssh-ed25519` at the start and your email at the end).

> On Arch with X11/Wayland, you can pipe directly to clipboard:
> ```bash
> # X11 (using xclip — install with: sudo pacman -S xclip)
> cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub | xclip -selection clipboard
>
> # Wayland (using wl-copy — install with: sudo pacman -S wl-clipboard)
> cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub | wl-copy
> ```

**Step A5: Add the public key to GitHub.**

1. Go to [github.com/settings/keys](https://github.com/settings/keys)
2. Click **"New SSH key"**
3. Title: something descriptive like `Arch Linux - Main Machine`
4. Key type: **Authentication**
5. Paste your public key into the "Key" field
6. Click **"Add SSH key"**

**Step A6: Test the connection.**

```bash
ssh -T git@github.com
```

You should see:

```
Hi YOURUSERNAME! You've been successfully authenticated, but GitHub does not provide shell access.
```

If you see this, SSH is working. If you see "Permission denied," double-check that you added the correct public key and that your private key is loaded in the agent (`ssh-add -l` to list loaded keys).

**Step A7: Use the SSH remote URL.**

When adding the remote, use the SSH URL format instead of HTTPS:

```bash
# If you already added the HTTPS remote, switch it:
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git

# Or if adding fresh:
git remote add origin git@github.com:YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git
```

Note the format difference:
- HTTPS: `https://github.com/YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git`
- SSH: `git@github.com:YOURUSERNAME/achilles.git`

From now on, `git push` and `git pull` use SSH automatically. No passwords, no tokens, no prompts.

---

#### Option B: HTTPS with Git Credential Helper

If you prefer HTTPS (simpler setup, works through firewalls that block SSH port 22):

**Step B1: Create a Personal Access Token (PAT).**

1. Go to [github.com/settings/tokens](https://github.com/settings/tokens?type=beta) (Fine-grained tokens)
2. Click **"Generate new token"**
3. Token name: `achilles-dev`
4. Expiration: 90 days (you can regenerate later)
5. Repository access: **"All repositories"** (or select just `achilles`)
6. Permissions → Repository permissions → Contents: **Read and write**
7. Click **"Generate token"**
8. **Copy the token immediately** — you won't see it again

**Step B2: Configure Git to cache your credentials.**

On Arch Linux, use the `git-credential-libsecret` helper to store credentials securely in your system keyring:

```bash
# Install the libsecret credential helper
sudo pacman -S libsecret

# Tell Git to use it
git config --global credential.helper /usr/lib/git-core/git-credential-libsecret
```

> If you don't want to use a keyring, a simpler (less secure) option:
> ```bash
> # Cache credentials in memory for 8 hours
> git config --global credential.helper 'cache --timeout=28800'
> ```

**Step B3: Push — enter credentials once.**

```bash
git push -u origin main
```

When prompted:
- Username: your GitHub username
- Password: **paste your Personal Access Token** (NOT your GitHub password)

The credential helper stores it. Future pushes won't prompt again.

---

#### Option C: GitHub CLI (`gh`)

The fastest way to handle authentication if you don't want to deal with keys or tokens manually.

```bash
# Install on Arch Linux
sudo pacman -S github-cli

# Authenticate
gh auth login
```

Follow the interactive prompts:
1. **GitHub.com** (not Enterprise)
2. **SSH** (recommended) or HTTPS
3. If SSH: it offers to generate and upload a key for you automatically
4. If HTTPS: it opens a browser for OAuth login — no token needed

After `gh auth login`, Git push/pull just works. `gh` also gives you CLI access to GitHub features: `gh pr create`, `gh pr list`, `gh repo view`, etc.

