## Part 3: Understanding Merge Strategies

Git has different ways to integrate branches. Understanding them now prevents confusion later.

### Fast-Forward Merge

When `main` hasn't moved since you branched, Git just moves the `main` pointer forward. No merge commit created.

```
Before:                        After fast-forward merge:
main                           
  ↓                            
  A ← B ← C ← D ← E          A ← B ← C ← D ← E
                    ↑                              ↑
                  feature                         main, feature
```

This happens when you run `git merge feature` and there's nothing new on `main` since the branch was created. Git says: "No divergence, I'll just move the pointer."

### Three-Way Merge (What You Just Did)

When both branches have new commits, Git creates a merge commit with two parents.

```
Before:                        After three-way merge:
      F ← G (feature)                F ← G
     /                               /     \
A ← B ← C ← D (main)          A ← B ← C ← D ← M (main)
                                              merge commit
```

The merge commit `M` has two parents: `D` (main's tip) and `G` (feature's tip). It records the act of combining the branches.

### When Conflicts Happen

Conflicts occur during three-way merges when both branches modify the same lines. Git can auto-merge changes to different files, or even different parts
of the same file. It only asks for help when the same lines are touched.

**Why this matters for Achilles:** On Day G3 you'll learn about **rebase**, which avoids merge commits entirely by replaying your commits on top of `main`.
For a solo project like Achilles, rebase produces a cleaner history. But understanding merge first is essential — rebase is a merge strategy, not a replacement.

