## Part 4: The Pull Request Workflow

This is the workflow you will use for **every single feature** from Phase 1 onward. Memorize it:

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              THE PROFESSIONAL FEATURE WORKFLOW                    │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                                  │
│  1. git checkout main                                            │
│  2. git pull origin main              ← Get latest               │
│  3. git checkout -b phase-N/feature   ← Create branch            │
│  4. Write code. Commit frequently.    ← Small, atomic commits    │
│  5. git push origin phase-N/feature   ← Push branch              │
│  6. Open Pull Request on GitHub       ← Describe the change      │
│  7. Review your own diff              ← Would a stranger get it? │
│  8. Merge the PR                      ← main advances            │
│  9. git checkout main && git pull     ← Update local              │
│ 10. git branch -d phase-N/feature     ← Clean up                 │
│                                                                  │
│  Branch naming convention:                                       │
│    phase-1/subprocess-runner                                     │
│    phase-2/adc-host-struct                                       │
│    phase-4/dag-builder                                           │
│    phase-7/nmap-node                                             │
│                                                                  │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Why open PRs even when solo?**

1. **Record:** Each PR is a timestamped, permanent record of what you built and why. It's a diary of your development.
2. **Diff review:** The PR diff view forces you to read your changes as a reviewer would. You will catch bugs, dead code, and unclear variable names that you missed while writing.
3. **Portfolio:** Hiring managers browse your PRs. A well-described PR with clean commits is a stronger signal than 10,000 lines in a single commit.
4. **Habit:** When you collaborate (and you will), this workflow is mandatory. Learning it solo means it's already muscle memory when it matters.

