## Part 5: Key Concepts to Internalize

| Question | Your Answer Should Include |
|----------|--------------------------|
| What is a branch? | A lightweight pointer to a commit (a 41-byte file with a hash) |
| What does `git checkout -b feature` do? | Creates a new branch at the current commit AND switches HEAD to it |
| What is `origin`? | The conventional name for your primary remote repository (GitHub) |
| What does `git push -u origin main` do? | Pushes `main` to the remote `origin` and sets it as the upstream tracking branch |
| What is a merge commit? | A commit with two parents, created when integrating diverged branches |
| What causes a conflict? | Two branches modifying the same lines of the same file |
| What do `<<<<<<<`, `=======`, `>>>>>>>` mean? | Conflict markers: current branch version, separator, incoming branch version |
| What is a Pull Request? | A GitHub feature for reviewing, discussing, and merging branches — the unit of code review |
| Why have branches? | Isolate experimental work from stable code — `main` always compiles |
| What's a fast-forward merge? | When `main` hasn't diverged, Git just moves the pointer — no merge commit |
| Why open PRs even solo? | Record, self-review via diff, portfolio signal, habit for collaboration |

